b" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="reqr"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Suggested Reading   Industry News</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:reqlea"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">ABI.BT BUD G/FDA HEIA.AE HEINY I/BVG I/DST I/RES I/RLO M/LEAH M/NCY MBW.XX N/FCG N/GEN N/HLT N/LIF R/NME R/US TGIF.XX </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday BEER BEVERAGES CALORIE COUNT CALORIES FDA HOW MANY CALORIES IN A SERVING OF LIQUOR MARGARITA MENU QUIZ SERVING SPIRITS TEST YOUR KNOWLEDGE WHICH HAS MORE CALORIES WINE SB126955385469309739639045841173800941564941 Wootan, Margo SYND CODES_REVIEWED Business </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OUSB </DescField><DescField fid="ipccodj">HEIA.AE </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Business</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">What, Cocktails Have Calories? New Rules Will Show How Many; Public-health researchers hope the new requirement will not only raise awareness but also spur drinkers to cut back</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>A new rule requiring restaurant chains to list calories for their alcoholic drinks poses a conundrum for makers of beer, wine and booze: Will drinkers change their habits?</Para><Para>Starting in May, the Food and Drug Administration will require chains like Applebee's and TGI Fridays to list calories next to all their menu items. That includes alcohol.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Menus at Chili's, for instance, will soon tell patrons a margarita packs 300 calories and a 12-ounce bottle of Budweiser contains 150.</Para><Para>For the first time restaurants across the country will have to list the caloric content of alcoholic beverages, though some outlets in states like New York and California already do so. In an industry where calories have been a relative mystery, the federal rule—which applies to chains with 20 or more outlets—will provide a new level of transparency about the often-overlooked calories in alcohol.</Para><Para>Public-health researchers hope the new requirement will not only raise awareness but also spur drinkers to cut back.</Para><Para>"If you don't want to get the 400 calories from an alcoholic beverage, you can easily swap for free water," said Margo G. Wootan, vice president for nutrition at the Center for Science in the Public Interest, a Washington-based consumer-advocacy group that lobbied the FDA to include alcoholic drinks in the new rules.</Para><Para>Studies have found calorie counts can influence food choices. Cochrane, a health-focused research network, last month published findings showing that when food <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fda-extends-deadline-for-listing-calories-on-menus-1436462336">calories are disclosed on menus</ELink>, diners' orders have 7.8% fewer calories.</Para><Para>Research on how calorie counts affect drinking are scant, but there is some evidence that such information might curb consumption. A study published last year in the academic journal Preventive Medicine estimated that imbibers in jurisdictions with menu-labeling requirements consumed on average 2% less alcohol than those in locales without mandates.</Para><Para>What motivates people to order a celebratory cocktail or a glass of wine can overpower concern about their waistlines. "People who want to drink a margarita are going to drink a margarita because they like the drink and it tastes good," said Frank Coleman, head of public affairs at the Distilled Spirits Council of the U.S., the industry's main trade body. "People concerned about calories will choose to have something like tequila, club soda and lime."</Para><Para>Until now, most drinkers haven't had a lot to go on in terms of calorie information. Some brewers print the calories in their beer on bottles and cans, but the practice isn't widespread. Wineries and spirits makers rarely list calories on their products, though some make them available online.</Para><Para>Laura Burke, a 22-year-old emergency medical technician in Hoboken, N.J., was shocked to discover the two margaritas she recently drank at a dinner out contained close to 1,000 calories in total.</Para><Para>"My jaw just dropped," Ms. Burke said after googling the calorie count. "I do think it would impact my decision making," she said, if menus carried calorie counts.</Para><Para>Back in 2011, <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704530204576237203366549010">when the FDA first released proposed menu-labeling rules</ELink>, it suggested excluding alcohol altogether since the U.S. Treasury has responsibility for most alcohol labeling, a legacy of Prohibition. The alcohol industry supported the exclusion.</Para><Para><ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/federal-government-to-mandate-more-calorie-counts-1416878402">The FDA reversed itself</ELink> In 2014 in a surprise move, citing a flood of comments detailing the health benefits of disclosing calorie counts for booze.</Para><Para>That's when the industry split into two camps: distillers versus big brewers.</Para><Para>Distillers pushed to ensure the new requirement would exclude the often high-calorie mixers that accompany a shot of spirits. Distillers trade group Discus advocated a method that would list calories by generic beverage type, rather than by specific brand. It found an unlikely ally in the Brewers Association, which represents small U.S. beer makers—who also favored generic calorie counts, saying these would be less costly.</Para><Para>The method suggested by distillers and small brewers assigns a calorie count of 96 to a 1.5-ounce shot of 80-proof gin, rum, vodka, or whiskey; it gives a 5-ounce glass of wine, red or white, 122 calories. A 12-ounce bottle of regular beer gets 153 calories, and a light beer 103 calories.</Para><Para>By that measure spirits look like the healthiest choice. Add mixers, though, and that beer starts looking a lot better calorie-wise. The Beer Institute, the trade body for big brewers, lobbied for calorie counts to be disclosed for individual brands and full drinks, including mixers. The FDA ultimately decided along these lines.</Para><Para>Large brewers have tried to use the calorie discrepancy as a way of fighting back after years of market-share losses to spirits makers. Beer made up 46% of all U.S. alcoholic beverage sales in 2017, down from 50% in 2002, according to Euromonitor. Over this same period, spirits' share rose to 32% from 29%, while wine climbed to 20% from 17%.</Para><Para>Two years ago, big beer makers like Anheuser-Busch InBev SA, MillerCoors and Heineken NV<ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/major-u-s-brewers-will-add-nutrition-labels-by-2020-1468351514">said they would voluntarily disclose calories</ELink>, alcohol content and other nutritional information on their labels by the end of 2020, in an attempt to woo drinkers back from spirits and wine.</Para><Para>"The beverage alcohol business in the U.S. is very competitive," said Beer Institute Chief Executive Jim McGreevy. "You have to fight for consumers every day."</Para><Para>Write to Saabira Chaudhuri at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:saabira.chaudhuri@wsj.com">saabira.chaudhuri@wsj.com</ELink></Para><Para>Related Coverage</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/does-america-really-need-another-light-beer-corona-thinks-so-1520341200">Does America Really Need Another Light Beer? Corona Thinks So</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/booze-makers-court-consumers-with-healthier-drinks-1469392485">Booze Makers Court Consumers With 'Healthier' Drinks</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-science-make-alcohol-safer-1508762361">Can Science Make Alcohol Safer?</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Saabira Chaudhuri </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-cocktails-have-calories-new-rules-will-show-how-many-1521813600" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

